      "Based on my search, I was unable to find specific discussions from Reddit about the GitHub Copilot and Claude Sonnet 4.6 integration from February 2026. However, I found several relevant sources discussing the integration and user feedback from other platforms. Here's what I found:\n\n## GitHub Copilot + Claude 4.6 Integration Overview\n\n### Official Integration Status\nAccording to Microsoft's developer changelog and GitHub blog posts, **Claude Opus 4.6** became generally available in GitHub Copilot in **February 2026** for Copilot Enterprise, Business, Pro, and Pro+ subscribers. The model is accessible in GitHub Copilot Chat on github.com, VS Code (chat, ask, edit, agent modes), Visual Studio, GitHub Mobile, and CLI.\n\n### Claude Sonnet 4.6 Release (February 18, 2026)\nClaude Sonnet 4.6 was released on February 18, 2026, and GitHub Copilot has integrated this latest model as well.\n\n## User Feedback & Reviews Summary\n\n### Positive Feedback\n\n1. **Performance Improvements**\n   - In internal Anthropic testing, users preferred **Sonnet 4.6 over Sonnet 4.5 in 70% of cases**\n   - More impressively, **59% of users preferred Sonnet 4.6 over Opus 4.5** (the previous flagship model)\n   - Users reported better instruction following, fewer instances of \"laziness\" or over-engineering, and more stable multi-step task execution\n\n2. **Code Quality**\n   - Users noted Sonnet 4.6 **reads context more carefully before making code changes**\n   - It **merges duplicate logic** rather than copying and pasting code\n   - Hallucinations reduced by approximately 70%\n   - False success claims significantly decreased\n\n3. **Long Context Window**\n   - Sonnet 4.6 supports **1 million token context window** (beta)\n   - Users reported this is critical for handling large codebases without losing context\n\n4. **Frontend & Visual Capabilities**\n   - Multiple users reported improved frontend code generation\n   - Visual outputs described as more refined with better layout, animations, and design sense\n\n### Concerns & Criticisms\n\n1. **Security Concerns**\n   - Some developers expressed concern about **Agent mode security** in Copilot\n   - Worries about agents with production commit permissions posing supply chain risks if workflows are compromised\n\n2. **Opus 4.6 Performance**\n   - Some users felt Opus 4.6 didn't meet expectations compared to Sonnet 4.6\n   - Opus 4.6 recommended mainly for backend, question answering, and tool calling, while Sonnet 4.6 preferred for coding\n\n### GitHub Copilot Multi-Model Strategy\n- GitHub's strategy of integrating multiple AI models (Claude, GPT-5.3-Codex, Gemini) allows developers to choose different models for different tasks\n- This is seen as a response to competition from Cursor (which popularized Claude integration)\n\n---\n\n**Note**: I couldn't locate specific Reddit discussions (r/programming, r/github, etc.) about this topic, likely because:\n1. The content may be newer or less indexed\n2. Discussions might be happening in private communities or other forums\n3. The specific combination of search terms didn't match Reddit post titles\n\nFor the most current Reddit discussions, you may want to search directly on reddit.com for terms like \"Claude 4.6\", \"Sonnet 4.6 Copilot\", or check relevant subreddits manually."
